accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe gap between the theory and the practice of working with Black and minority ethnic groups presents an ongoing conundrum for social work. This exciting textbook presents a new theory based on a rich understanding of the constraints and creativities of practice. Taking a transformative approach, this accessible textbook presents evidence from both academics and practitioners. Contributions draw on real-life practice scenarios and present case studies to illustrate the many dimensions of working in a diverse society, encouraging students and practitioners to form innovative solutions to service delivery. Covering practice themes including risk, co-production, interpreting, multi-disciplinary working and personalisation, this is vital reading for all students in social work, and practitioners undertaking continuing professional development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aSocial work with immigrantszGreat BritainvCase studies. 0aSocial work with minoritieszGreat BritainvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnand, Janet Carter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Tue Hong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhatti-Sinclair, Kish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Beverley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCemlyn, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Chaitali, econtribu